	<section xml:id="manual.know.status-led">
		<title>Status LED</title>
		<para>The status LED has a very simple and traditional design. When you receive a signal it turns green, when you transmit it turns red, and it's off in standby.</para>
	</section>
	<section xml:id="manual.know.call-key">
		<title>Side key 1 - CALL (Broadcast FM and Alarm)</title>
		<para>Press
			<inlinemediaobject>
				<imageobject>
					<imagedata contentdepth="0.9em" format="png" fileref="figs/key-call.svg.png"/>
				</imageobject>
			</inlinemediaobject>
			momentarily to start the broadcast FM receiver. Another momentary press turns the broadcast FM receiver off.</para>
		<para>Press and hold
			<inlinemediaobject>
				<imageobject>
					<imagedata contentdepth="0.9em" format="png" fileref="figs/key-call.svg.png"/>
				</imageobject>
			</inlinemediaobject>
			to activate the alarm function. Press and hold again to turn it off.</para>
	</section>
	<section xml:id="manual.know.monitor-key">
		<title>Side key 2 - MONI (Monitor and Flashlight)</title>
		<para>Press
			<inlinemediaobject>
				<imageobject>
					<imagedata contentdepth="0.9em" format="png" fileref="figs/key-moni.svg.png"/>
				</imageobject>
			</inlinemediaobject>
			momentarily to turn on the LED flashlight. Another momentary press turns the flashlight off.</para>
		<para>Press and hold
			<inlinemediaobject>
				<imageobject>
					<imagedata contentdepth="0.9em" format="png" fileref="figs/key-moni.svg.png"/>
				</imageobject>
			</inlinemediaobject>
			to monitor the signal. This will open up the squelch so you can listen to the unfiltered signal.</para>
	</section>
	<section xml:id="manual.know.mode-key">
		<title>VFO / MR -mode key</title>
		<para>Pressing 
			<inlinemediaobject>
				<imageobject>
					<imagedata contentdepth="0.9em" format="png" fileref="figs/key-mode.svg.png"/>
				</imageobject>
			</inlinemediaobject>
			switches between Frequency (VFO) Mode and Memory (MR) mode. Memory mode is sometimes also referred to as Channel mode.</para>
	</section>
	<section xml:id="manual.know.ab-key">
		<title>A / B select key</title>
		<para>The 
			<inlinemediaobject>
				<imageobject>
					<imagedata contentdepth="0.9em" format="png" fileref="figs/key-ab.svg.png"/>
				</imageobject>
			</inlinemediaobject>
			key switches the display between your selected A and B bands or channels.</para>
	</section>
	<section xml:id="manual.know.band-key">
		<title>Band key</title>
		<para>Switches between bands?</para>
	</section>
	<section xml:id="manual.know.keypad">
		<title>Numeric keypad</title>
		<para>The Baofeng UV-5R hand-held transceiver comes standard with a full numeric keypad.</para>
		<figure xml:id="manual.radio.keypad-fig">
			<title>Baofeng UV-5R, keypad</title>
			<mediaobject>
				<imageobject>
					<imagedata fileref="figs/keypad.svg.png" contentdepth="4.6em" />
				</imageobject>
			</mediaobject>
		</figure>
		<para>The numeric keys have their secondary function printed on them (in reality it's rather menu short-cuts, more on that in <xref linkend="manual.menu"/>).</para>
		<para>The
			<inlinemediaobject>
				<imageobject>
					<imagedata contentdepth="0.9em" format="png" fileref="figs/key-star.svg.png"/>
				</imageobject>
			</inlinemediaobject>
			and
			<inlinemediaobject>
				<imageobject>
					<imagedata contentdepth="0.9em" format="png" fileref="figs/key-pound.svg.png"/>
				</imageobject>
			</inlinemediaobject>
			keys on the other hand have actual secondary functions, scan and keypad lock respectively.</para>
		<section>
			<title>Pound key</title>
			<para>To enable or disable the keypad lock, press and hold the
				<inlinemediaobject>
					<imageobject>
						<imagedata contentdepth="0.9em" format="png" fileref="figs/key-pound.svg.png"/>
					</imageobject>
				</inlinemediaobject>
				key for about two seconds.</para>
			<para>In channel mode,
				<inlinemediaobject>
					<imageobject>
						<imagedata contentdepth="0.9em" format="png" fileref="figs/key-pound.svg.png"/>
					</imageobject>
				</inlinemediaobject>
				also acts as a transmit power short key. While in channel mode, momentarily press
				<inlinemediaobject>
					<imageobject>
						<imagedata contentdepth="0.9em" format="png" fileref="figs/key-pound.svg.png"/>
					</imageobject>
				</inlinemediaobject>
				to change between High and Low transmit power.</para>
		</section>
		<section>
			<title>Star key</title>
			<para>To enable the scanner, press and hold the
				<inlinemediaobject>
					<imageobject>
						<imagedata contentdepth="0.9em" format="png" fileref="figs/key-star.svg.png"/>
					</imageobject>
				</inlinemediaobject>
				key for about two seconds. This also works when listening to broadcast FM.</para>
		</section>
		<section>
			<title>Menu and function keys</title>
			<para>The
				<inlinemediaobject>
					<imageobject>
						<imagedata contentdepth="0.9em" format="png" fileref="figs/key-exit.svg.png"/>
					</imageobject>
				</inlinemediaobject>
				key, used to enter the menu and confirm menu options.</para>	
			<para>The
				<inlinemediaobject>
					<imageobject>
						<imagedata contentdepth="0.9em" format="png" fileref="figs/key-up.svg.png"/>
					</imageobject>
				</inlinemediaobject>
				and 
				<inlinemediaobject>
					<imageobject>
						<imagedata contentdepth="0.9em" format="png" fileref="figs/key-down.svg.png"/>
					</imageobject>
				</inlinemediaobject>
				keys are used to navigate through the menu as well as select channels and step up or down in frequency (depending on operating mode).</para>
			<para>The
				<inlinemediaobject>
					<imageobject>
						<imagedata contentdepth="0.9em" format="png" fileref="figs/key-exit.svg.png"/>
					</imageobject>
				</inlinemediaobject>
				key is used to exit menus and cancel menu options.</para>
			<para>For a more in-depth explanation on how to work the menu see <xref linkend="manual.menu"/>.</para>
		</section>
	</section>
	<section xml:id="manual.know.port">
		<title>Accessory jack</title>
		<para>The accessory jack on the Baofeng UV-5R is a Kenwood compatible two(2)-pin design.</para>
		<figure xml:id="manual.radio.headset-fig">
			<title>Typical 2 pin Kenwood headset configuration.</title>
			<mediaobject>
				<imageobject>
					<imagedata fileref="figs/kenwood-2pin-headset.svg.png" contentwidth="8cm" />
				</imageobject>
			</mediaobject>
		</figure>
		<para>The Kenwood 2-pin connector has one 3.5mm TRS plug, and one 2.5mm TS plug, spaced 12mm apart.</para>
	</section>
